text.text: A Guide to Tufnell Park

Contrary to what you might have heard, this often forgotten area of London has penty more to offer than that fantastically grimy venue The Dome. We kicked it in this eclectic little nugget and took its myriad of buzzing haunts for a spin.
Best for... late night jams

tip.text: A venue with one hell of a devotion to rock'n'roll. Bursting with energy, live music and perhaps most importantly delicious pizza, Aces and Eights is open ‘til a whopping 2.30am on Fridays and Saturdays – making it Tufnell’s staple late night joint. The beautifully lit, low-ceilinged basement is a spectacular spot to catch some lesser known musical mixtures, go for some booze and some wholesome guitar-smashing fun.

The warmly lit, cosy basement is a spectacular spot to catch some lesser-known musical mixtures. Go for some booze and some wholesome guitar-smashing fun.
Best for... healthy breakfasts

tip.text: This dapper little café is the area’s most tasteful spot for satisfying all your caffeine and muffin needs. Along with all your granola, sourdough toast, grilled halloumi, soup and poached eggs needs. Cleverly decorated with a green patch outside and a luxuriating ambient soundtrack to boot – you’ll never step foot in a Starbucks again.

Best for... keeping trim

tip.text: Behind a set of enormous red, heavy wooden doors in Tufnell Park lies a stunning testament to China’s 1500-year-old temple. Home to the ancient art and spiritual practice of Shaolin kung fu, this mesmerising building holds everything you’d need to lead a full Shaolin life: seminar rooms, a fighting ring, a meditation room, a sauna and of course an immemorial order of warriors ready to teach kids as young as 5 kung fu. If you’re packing relentless determination, nerves of steel and a thirst for new cultures – you know where to head.

tip.text: While Tufnell Park is by no means short of banging pubs, The Pineapple might just take the biscuit. Tucked away from the buzz of the main road yet fantastically rowdy in its own right – the spectacular crew behind this North London boozer know exactly what’s up. This beautiful listed building is home to guaranteed romping good times, with ‘Cheese Thursdays’ (donate £3 to a colossal pub cheeseboard and dig in knowing your change is going to the homeless), a stellar Thai kitchen upstairs and £5 lunches. Oh, and there’s two pub cats with a penchant for prawns and scuttling around the place. Meow.

Best for... craft beer nerds

tip.text: If it’s an elaborate drink you’re after, craft beer haunt The Rose and Crown will most definitely have you covered. Boasting an inspiringly eclectic lineup of rotating bevvies and ever honing the spotlight on small, local and quite often crazy breweries – you can expect to wrap your gob around everything from shortbread-flavoured beer to tropical punch-flavoured beer and everything in between. Also on the cards is an incredibly unique and innovative snack menu, live music, comedy nights and a spectacularly dingy, club-like basement that’s available for hire.

tip.text: The dishes whisked up at Lalibela are, quite simply, lurrvely - if you have quite a serious amount of time on your hands. Slow-cooked, thoughtful and rich – each dish is tender and lush, but maybe not the best idea for a quick lunch break. Still, while you're waiting, check out the artwork, which is imported straight from the motherland and includes some really stunning pieces. In terms of what to order, try the grilled injera and cheese, lentil samosas and the chicken spinach tibs. Be sure to give the small but sharp selection of Ethiopian beers a whirl too.

tip.text:
It may be one venue, but there's a whole lot going on here. During the day, Korova is a sweet little cafe doing breakfast and brunch - eggs done just right, a cheeky Bloody Mary here and there. In the evening though the cocktails really start to flow, and the menu opens up - think moules marinière or moules provençale served with skinny fries, or saffron risotto with butternut squash.

The cocktails mixed at the art deco bar are really special though. One of their signature concoctions combines Courvoisier XO, Cointreau, orange bitters and champagne. If you're in Tufnell Park, this should be a regular for you.

text.text: Original art deco interior and European-inspired dishes make this a hotspot with the locals around these parts. With an elegant, family-run night-time restaurant, a menu that changes with the seasons and only features locally-sourced ingredients, and an award-winning cocktail menu to boot, you'll want to pop in to Korova on your Tufnell crawl.
Best for... WFH

tip.text:
This is a 'literary cafe', which basically means the walls are lined with books, and everyone in here is working on their short stories. TBF, it makes for a pretty good working environment: It's cosy and comfortable with plenty of plug sockets. Plus, there's nothing quite like procrastinating over a slice of homemade carrot cake.

They have lovely little outdoor space and all of your usual café goodies like wraps, paninis, and quiches. Grab a steaming hot cwup of cwoffee and get cracking on that novella. Or don't, we won't judge.

text.text: This is one of those cosy little cafés that doubles up as a working space because there's nothing quite like procrastinating over a slice of homemade carrot cake. It's perfectly cosy, with a lovely little outdoor space and much of your usual café goodies, like wraps, quiches and homely coffee-smelling vibes.
Best for... eating without the distraction of a menu

tip.text:
Indecisiveness and menu fuss are completely removed from the equation at Del Parc, where the only thing you need to worry about is giving them your dietary requirements when you book a table. What do you eat? Well, expert chef Steven Morrish will see to that, taking you on a creative and tasty foodie journey through Spain and North Africa.

This isn’t traditional tapas - they prefer the term sharing plates - but you may well see the likes of Galician mussels, Moroccan lamb meatballs or black tiger prawns with chilli, garlic, white wine and lemon. Then again, you might not - it’s all guesswork really, which we think is pretty exciting. All wines come from the Iberian Peninsular, which makes for apt drinking in Del Parc.

text.text: Indecisiveness and menu fuss is taken out of the equation at Del Parc, where expert chef Steven Morrish takes you on a sharing plate journey through Spain and North Africa. What's on the menu is really up to the head honcho, but you might expect to see stuff like Galician mussels, Moroccan lamb meatballs or black tiger prawns with chilli, garlic, white wine and lemon.
Best for... satisfying your sweet tooth

tip.text:
If you're in the Tufnell Park area on a hot day you'll likely catch locals screaming for Ruby Violet's homemade ice cream (or maybe just queueing up politely). Ruby's is a prime destination for creative, delicate and ever-changing flavours. Wacky favourites include walnut, fig and honey; lime and star anise sorbet; and the seasonal stilton and cranberry. (Say what?)

Ruby earns extra points from us for having funky interiors and dedication to presentation. Pop in for teas, coffees, desserts and even the extra indulgent ice cream sandwich.
